data: # Lesson 24: Set the frequency of a buzzer from web

## 1 Overview

In this lesson you will learn how to turn On and Off a buzzer and control its frequency from a web browser.

## 3 Connections
Below you can find the schematic:
Also, you can find below a visual representation of the project:

## 4 Code

The code for this lesson is an advanced version of the one from the previous lesson, because we will add a slider to control the frequency of the buzzer, where in the previous one, the frequency was fixed. Also, in this code we will send data to the server and the server will send data to the client.

The beginning of the code is identical with the one from the previous lesson: import the libraries, declare the pin used by the buzzer. For this code we will need another two variables, one that will store the state of the button **(container)** and one that will store the last frequency read from the slider **(frequency)**. We will need these two variables because we will want the send them back to the web page when the page is reloaded so the web page will look the same even if the page will be reloaded.

Next, we have to deal with the routes for our user interface. For that, we need a route to the default location, which is â/â. For this route we have created a function that uses **template** to send the **index.html** page to the default location.

Next, we will have a **route** for the button from the web page. This route has a function attached and in this function we will let our code know that we are working with global variables so that we can use the values from of these variables. Next step is to request from the web page the state of the button and, depending on the value returned, we will turn On or Off the buzzer at the frequency given by or **frequency** variable.

The **buzzer_frequency()** function is triggered when any change is made to the slider. The main instruction in this function is **frequency = int(request.POST.get('sound'))**, which translates the value of the slider sent to the server using an **ajax** call. This value is stored in the **frequency** variable. Using an **if** statement and the value of the **container**, we will decide whether the buzzer will be turned On at the specified frequency or will be turned Off.

The last function needed is **refresh()**. This function will be triggered each time the page will be reloaded and will send to user the last state of the button and the last frequency set by the slider.

The code will end with a **run** call that will listen to HTTP requests on all interfaces. This run is located inside a **try-except** block so that when we will interrupt the connection, we can stop the buzzer.

The HTML page is similar with the one from the previous lesson. The head is similar, only in the **css_off** css class the color is changed from **white** to **lightgray**.

In the HTML **body** we will add a row for the slider, and another that will display in real time the frequency of the buzzer.

In the JavaScript part, the instruction **$(document).ready(refreshFunction)** is used to trigger the refreshFunction every time the HTML page is reloaded. The **refreshFunction** contains a **getJSON** instruction that will read from the server the last registered state for the button and also the last frequency. Using these values, the visual representation of the page will remain the same after reloading the page.

Next, when the button is clicked it will trigger a function that will check for the class assigned to the speaker, and on the returned value, an **ajax** call will be made and will send to the server the state of the button **(On or Off)**. Also the text on the button will be changed and, also, the css class of the speaker.

The last part of the JavaScript is the one which deals with the slider. In a variable will be stored the value of the slider, this value will be displayed in the browser in the last row defined in the HTML **body**. Also, there is an **ajax** call that will send to the server the value of the slider, which will be the frequency of the buzzer.

"""
*   Credits: www.plusivo.com
*
*   Lesson 24: Set the frequency of a buzzer from web
*
*   The code below is created for the lesson "Set the frequency
*   of a buzzer from web", where you will learn
*   how to fully control a buzzer from a web browser.
*
*   Make sure you connected the buzzer correctly, as shown in the guide.
*
*   Before you run the code, do not forget to start the pigpiod daemon
*   using "sudo pigpiod".
*
*   More information about the connections can be found in the guide.
*
"""

#import the libraries used
from bottle import route, run, template, request
import pigpio

#create an instance of the pigpio library
pi = pigpio.pi()

#define the pin used by the Buzzer
#this is GPIO18, which is pin 12
buzzer = 18

#the following variable will be used
#to store the last state of the button (On or Off)
container = ''

#set the initial frequency of the buzzer
frequency = 500

#define the route for the main page
@route('/')
def index():
    #at the '/' route we will return the index.html
    #template that is in the views folder
    return template('index.html')

@route('/button_state', method = 'POST')
def button_state():
    global container
    global frequency

    #request data from web page
    container = request.POST.get('state')

    #if the value returned is "On", we will turn On the buzzer
    #else, we will turn Off the buzzer
    if container == 'On':
        #turn On the buzzer
        pi.hardware_PWM(buzzer, frequency, 500000)
    else:
        #turn off the buzzer
        pi.hardware_PWM(buzzer, 0, 0)

    #send a message to the user
    return 'ok'

@route('/buzzer_frequency', method = 'POST')
def buzzer_frequency():
    global frequency
    global container

    #request data from web page
    frequency = int(request.POST.get('sound'))

    if container == 'On':
        #turn On the buzzer
        pi.hardware_PWM(buzzer, frequency, 500000)
    else:
        #turn off the buzzer
        pi.hardware_PWM(buzzer, 0, 0)

    #send a message to the user
    return 'ok'

@route('/refresh')
def refresh():
    state = 0

    if container == 'On':
        state = 1

    #send the values to the client
    return {'state':state, 'frequency':frequency}

try:
    #we will run the app on port 5000
    run(host = '0.0.0.0', port = '5000')

except KeyboardInterrupt:
    pass

#stop the pwm signal
pi.hardware_PWM(buzzer, 0, 0)
